Some basics of mapping in R

Brittany Barker

2023-11-09

Load all required packages.

library(here) # Start in R project directory
library(dplyr) # Data wrangling
library(lubridate) # Working with dates
library(ggplot2) # Plotting model outputs
library(patchwork) # Combine plots
library(viridis) # Color palettes for ggplot2
library(knitr) # Including graphics
library(sf) # Working with spatial features
library(terra) # Working with rasters
library(USAboundaries) # Boundary features

Purpose of this demo

Provide some examples of using the terra, sf, and ggplot2 packages to work with geospatial data and create beautiful maps.

Mapping predicted vs.observed dates of lilac phenophases


In the following exercises, we will visualize spatial concordance between model-predicted and observed dates of lilac leaf out, which is a phenophase of lilac in which new leaves appear. A phenophase is an observable stage of an animals or plants life cycle that can be defined by a start and end point. All data were derived from the USA National Phenology Network, an organization that hosts phenology models and maintains a database of volunteer-contributed observations of phenology for ecologically and economically important species of plants and insects in the USA.

(1) Mapping predicted lilac leaf out

We import raster data for model predictions of lilac leaf out for 2018 using the rast() function in terra.

lilacModel <- rast(here("data", "lilac_2018_model.tiff"))

The raster is class SpatRaster. The rasters coordinate reference system is lon/lat NAD83 (often used for North America) and its values range from 6 to 223, which corresponds the day in which lilac leaf out was predicted to occur in 2018.

class(lilacModel)
## [1] "SpatRaster"
## attr(,"package")
## [1] "terra"
lilacModel
## class       : SpatRaster 
## dimensions  : 1228, 2606, 1  (nrow, ncol, nlyr)
## resolution  : 0.02246419, 0.02107085  (x, y)
## extent      : -125.0208, -66.47917, 24.0625, 49.9375  (xmin, xmax, ymin, ymax)
## coord. ref. : lon/lat NAD83 (EPSG:4269) 
## source      : lilac_2018_model.tiff 
## name        : layer 
## min value   :     6 
## max value   :   223

The raster can be visualized using the base plot() function in R. This function can produce some decent looking maps, but not nearly as nice as ggplot2 maps in my opinion. Plants develop slower in colder temperatures, which is why lilac leaf out occurs at later dates in higher-latitude and higher-elevation areas.

plot(lilacModel)

For plotting with ggplot2, we convert the raster to a data frame because geoms for gridded data (i.e., geom_raster() and geom_tile()) require data frames. Additionally, I have found that its often easier to manipulate data frames than rasters. However, I just discovered the tidyterra package, which has its own set of geoms for ggplot2 (e.g., geom_spatraster())! This is definitely something Ill investigate further.

Notice that as.data.frame() in the terra package retains coordination information (x and y columns) by setting the xy option to TRUE.

# Conver raster data to a data frame 
lilacModel_df <- terra::as.data.frame(lilacModel, xy = TRUE) 
head(lilacModel_df)
##               x        y layer
## 71692 -95.15470 49.35805   121
## 71693 -95.13223 49.35805   121
## 71694 -95.10977 49.35805   121
## 71695 -95.08731 49.35805   121
## 71696 -95.06484 49.35805   125
## 71697 -95.04238 49.35805   125

Well use a dplyr pipeline to rename() the data column to leaf_out, convert the day of year to a calendar date, and then use the floor_date() function from the lubridate package to bin the dates by week of the year.

# Reformat data
lilacModel_df2 <- lilacModel_df %>%
  rename(leaf_out_doy = layer) %>% # New column name
  mutate(leaf_out_date = as.Date(leaf_out_doy, origin = "2018-01-01")) %>% # Convert day of year to calendar date
  group_by(leaf_out_week = factor(lubridate::floor_date(leaf_out_date, 'week'))) %>% # Create bins of dates
  ungroup()

Notice that the data frame now has data in numerical (class num), date (class Date), and categorical (class factor) formats.

str(lilacModel_df2)
## tibble [1,753,552 x 5] (S3: tbl_df/tbl/data.frame)
##  $ x            : num [1:1753552] -95.2 -95.1 -95.1 -95.1 -95.1 ...
##  $ y            : num [1:1753552] 49.4 49.4 49.4 49.4 49.4 ...
##  $ leaf_out_doy : num [1:1753552] 121 121 121 121 125 125 125 125 126 133 ...
##  $ leaf_out_date: Date[1:1753552], format: "2018-05-02" "2018-05-02" ...
##  $ leaf_out_week: Factor w/ 30 levels "2018-01-07","2018-01-14",..: 17 17 17 17 18 18 18 18 18 19 ...

Now lets use ggplot2 to visualize the predicted week of lilac leaf out for 2018 (i.e., our raster). A custom scale function from the viridis package, scale_fill_viridis_d(), is used to color the discrete data (i.e., weeks of the year) from blue to yellow.

# Create a map using ggplot2
ggplot() + 
  geom_raster(data = lilacModel_df2, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = leaf_out_week)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d("Predicted 1st\nLeaf Out DOY", option = "viridis") +
  ggtitle("2018 Predicted Lilac Leaf Out")

This map looks okay, but it would arguably look better without the default gray background, grid lines, and axes features. If you plan on building multiple ggplots, its more concise to define your theme a single time rather than repeating it each time you make a new plot.

# Custom theme
my_theme <- theme(panel.grid= element_blank(),
                 panel.background = element_blank(), 
                 panel.border = element_blank(),
                 axis.title = element_blank(), 
                 axis.text = element_blank(),
                 axis.ticks = element_blank(),
                 title = element_text(face = "bold"),
                 legend.key.size = unit(0.4, "cm"))

Apply the custom theme to the plot.

# Create a map using ggplot2
ggplot() + 
  geom_raster(data = lilacModel_df2, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = leaf_out_week)) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d("Predicted 1st\nLeaf Out DOY", option = "viridis") +
  ggtitle("2018 Predicted Lilac Leaf Out") +  
  my_theme # Our custom theme

(2) Adding state features to map

The map is more informative if we add state boundaries. Well use an R package called USAboundaries to get these data using the us_states() function. In the pipeline, we subset data for the contiguous U.S. (CONUS) using filter(). The feature is projected to the the NAD83 coordiante reference system and converted to a multi-line string using st_cast().

# Simple feature ("sf") for US states
states <- us_states(resolution = "high") %>%
  filter(jurisdiction_type == "state" & !name %in% c("Alaska", "Hawaii")) %>%
  st_transform(crs = 4269) %>%
  st_cast("MULTILINESTRING")

The code block below is the same as above except it adds the states feature.

# Create a map using ggplot2
ggplot() + 
  geom_raster(data = lilacModel_df2, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = leaf_out_week)) +
  geom_sf(data = states) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d("Week of Predicted\n1st Leaf Out", option = "viridis") + 
  ggtitle("2018 Predicted Lilac Leaf Out") +
  my_theme

(3) Adding phenometric data to the map

How do model-predicted dates of lilac leaf out compared with observed dates? To answer this question, we import phenometric data for observed lilac leaf out dates for 2018. These data were collected by volunteers and submitted to the USA National Phenology Networks database.

# Phenometric data
lilacObs <- read.csv(here("data", "lilac_2018_obs.csv"))

Take a look at the data dimensions. We see that there are 182 observations (rows) and 25 variables.

dim(lilacObs)
## [1] 182  25

There are 77 unique sites in the dataset. Our goal is to add data for each of these sites to the map.

length(unique(lilacObs$site_id))
## [1] 77

We only need data in three columns in the phenometric data: longitude, latitude, and first_yes_doy. The first_yes_doy column specifies which day of year that lilacs first had leaf out at the site. Well subset the columns using select() and take a look at the first several rows of data.

lilacObs <- lilacObs %>%
  filter(state != "ON") %>% # Remove an observation from Canada
  dplyr::select("longitude", "latitude", "first_yes_doy") # Subset data by column

Take a look at the first several rows of data.

head(lilacObs)
##   longitude latitude first_yes_doy
## 1 -87.89300 43.09780           121
## 2 -87.89300 43.09780           121
## 3 -92.75200 36.52450            53
## 4 -83.05769 43.72269           118
## 5 -76.55337 38.88813            57
## 6 -76.55337 38.88813            57

To match the format of the model-predicted data, day of year is converted to a calendar date and then binned by week of the year.

lilacObs2 <- lilacObs %>%
  mutate(leaf_out_date = as.Date(first_yes_doy, origin = "2018-01-01")) %>%
  group_by(leaf_out_week = factor(lubridate::floor_date(leaf_out_date, 'week')))

For plotting purposes, we convert the phenometric data to a simple feature (sf) object using the st_as_sf() function. We tell the function which columns contain coordinate information and specify the crs argument as 4269, which corresponds to the NAD83 coordinate reference system.

# Convert data frame to a simple feature
lilacObs_sf <- st_as_sf(lilacObs2, coords = c("longitude", "latitude"), crs = 4269)

Now lets add the phenometric data so we can visualize spatial concordance between model-predicted and observed dates for first leaf out. Sites for each observation are plotted using their coordinate information and colored according to values in the leaf_out_date column.

# Add sites to the map
conus_map <- ggplot() + 
  geom_raster(data = lilacModel_df2, aes(x = x, y = y, fill = leaf_out_week)) +
  geom_sf(data = states) +
  geom_sf(data = lilacObs_sf, aes(color = leaf_out_date), size = 3, show.legend = FALSE) +
  scale_fill_viridis_d("Week of Predicted\n1st Leaf Out", option = "viridis") + 
  scale_color_viridis("Week of Observed\n1st Leaf Out", option = "viridis", 
                      guide = guide_colourbar(reverse = TRUE)) +
  ggtitle("2018 Predicted Lilac Leaf Out") +
  my_theme
conus_map

(4) Map interpretation

Our map indicates that observed dates of lilac leaf out in 2018 were often earlier than dates predicted by the model. This suggests that our model tends to over-predict this phenophase, and therefore may need to be calibrated. However, notice that two sites had dates that were much later than predicted dates. In this case, perhaps the volunteers failed to notice that lilac leaf out had already occurred, although other explanations are possible.

(5) Combining maps

Lets say were interested in results for Michigan and nearby areas in Wisconsin, so we want to create a new map that focuses just on these areas. One way to accomplish this task is to use the coord_sf() function, in which the x- and y-limits of the bounding box of interest are defined. We also remove the legend and title.

conus_map +
    coord_sf(xlim = c(-90.5542, -82.3047), 
           ylim = c(41.6311, 47.5739),
           expand = FALSE) + # Take limits exactly as defined
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        title = element_blank()) # Remove title and legend

In our final map, we also add county boundaries for the Michigan region, which can be downloaded via us_counties().

# Simple feature ("sf") for US counties
counties <- us_counties(resolution = "high") %>%
  st_transform(crs = 4269) %>%
  st_cast("MULTILINESTRING") 

# Final map for Michigan region
# Lilac leaf out observations are added again so boundary lines don't cover them
mi_map <- conus_map +
  geom_sf(data = counties) + # Add counties
  geom_sf(data = lilacObs_sf, aes(color = leaf_out_date), size = 3, show.legend = FALSE) +
  coord_sf(xlim = c(-90.5542, -82.3047), 
           ylim = c(41.6311, 47.5739),
           expand = FALSE) + # Take limits exactly as defined
  theme(legend.position = "none",
        title = element_blank())

Finally, we can combine maps for CONUS and the Michigan region using the patchwork package. Other options for combining plots include functions in the ggpubr (ggarrange()) and cowplot (plot_grid()) packages. The \ operator indicates that the map for CONUS goes on top of the Michigan region map, the width setting indicates that the CONUS is map is 2X bigger, and the legend is collected to ensure it stays in the correct position (on right-hand side).

# Combine maps
conus_map / mi_map +
  plot_layout(guides = "collect", widths = c(2, 1))

Wrap-up

I only scratched the surface of mapping in R!
- ggplot2 has several functions for plotting sf objects
- Raster data can be converted to data frames and plotted
- However, functions in tidyterra can directly plot SpatRaster rasters
- Another option is to convert the raster to a stars object and plot it with geom_stars()
